		<guid isPermaLink="false">http://marketingmusician.com/?p=2303</guid>
		<description>A call to action CTA shold be in your thoughts when you fire up an email. Even if its just to let people know where you are on twitter, facebook, etc, there is a goal. When you write a call to action you don&amp;#8217;t want to put &amp;#8220;Click here.&amp;#8221; I&amp;#8217;m guilty of that. A better ...</description>
			<content:encoded><![CDATA[<p>A call to action CTA shold be in your thoughts when you fire up an email. Even if its just to let people know where you are on twitter, facebook, etc, there is a goal. When you write a call to action you don&#8217;t want to put &#8220;Click here.&#8221; I&#8217;m guilty of that. A better way is to let people know <em>what</em> they are clicking on <em>where</em> it is taking them, and <em>why</em> they should click it.  Instead of saying, &#8220;click here&#8221; I could say,  &#8220;<a title="Build Your Band’s Website Details" href="http://marketingmusician.com/build-your-bands-website/">Find out about the Creating your band&#8217;s website class on our website, and see if its what you could benefit from the class</a>..  The example <a title="CTA skills from Fanbrdige" href="http://www.fanbridge.com/blog/creating-effective-calls-to-action-in-email-campaigns" target="_blank">in the article I was referencing</a> used the CTA of &#8220;See our site for more fan-only presale information.&#8221;</p>
<p>The other thing to think about is the location of your call to action. While many email programs insert these at the bottom, it doesn&#8217;t hurt to put these &#8220;above the fold&#8221; and use a warm friendly inviting tone.</p>
<p>Lastly, you don&#8217;t have to be a great web designer to make your call to action stand out. This be as simple as putting it in bold.</p>
